'''Constantina Zavitsanos''' is a [[conceptual art|conceptual]] [[feminist art]]ist.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/body-utopia_us_55e883b3e4b0aec9f3568080 Priscilla Frank, "'Body Utopia' Explores The Explosive Beauty Of Nonconforming Bodies" Huffington Post, 4 September 2015]</ref>  Her works are organized around themes of planning, contingency, debt, dependency and care.<ref>[http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/spring-2015-rd-season-speculation/ "R&D Season: SPECULATION Spring 2015" [[e-flux]], 2015]</ref> Zavitsanos is a part of disability community as a care provider and recipient. She lives in New York City and teaches at [[The New School]].  She is a recipient of the 2015 [[Wynn Newhouse Award]] presented to disabled artists.<ref>[http://www.wnewhouseawards.com/constantinazavitsanos.html Constantina Zavitsanos, Wynn Newhouse Award]</ref> She held a residency at [[The New Museum]] in March–September 2015,<ref>[http://www.newmuseum.org/pages/view/speculation "New Museum: Spring 2015 R&D Season: SPECULATION"]</ref> where she curated a series of collaborative events with artists [[Reina Gossett]], [[Park McArthur]], Caroline Key, and Soyoung Yoon, and academics Stefano Harney, [[Fred Moten]], and Denise Ferreira da Silva.

==Notable works==
*'''It was what I wanted now was nearly invisible''' (2013) is a stack of papers next to a wall. Four- and five-digit-long numbers are printed on the paper tracking Zavitsanos’ projected student loan debt over the next 25 years and the minimum income necessary to make monthly loan payments.  Corinna Kirsch of ArtFCity has described the work as a strong statement with limited means. As Kirsch put it, "if a loan officer handed me thousands of pages showing my future indebtedness, I might’ve rethought signing away my future."<ref>[http://artfcity.com/2013/06/14/looking-at-our-financial-future-the-2013-whitney-isp-studio-exhibition/ Corinna Kirsch, "Looking at Our Financial Future: The 2013 Whitney ISP Studio Exhibition" Art F City, JUNE 14, 2013.]</ref>
*'''Sweepstakes''' (2015) Zavitsanos was a plaintiff in a class action lawsuit brought against the New York Police Department for wrongful arrest during the [[2004 Republican National Convention protest activity|2004 GOP convention in New York]]. New York City settled the case in 2015. Zavitsanos incorporated her settlement into the art work "Sweepstakes" at the [[New Museum]] where viewers were given a portion of the settlement on a daily basis.<ref>[http://newmuseum.tumblr.com/post/123200412337/constantina-zavitsanos-sweepstakes-2015-visa "Constantina Zavitsanos, Sweepstakes, 2015" [[New Museum]] Tublr blog 2015]</ref>

