'''''Heta-uma''''' ({{lang|ja|ヘタウマ}} or {{lang|ja|ヘタうま}}) is a Japanese underground [[manga]] movement started in the 1970 decade with the magazine ''[[Garo (magazine)|Garo]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artreview.com/opinion/ara_spring_2015_opinion_paul_gravett/|title=The ‘bad but good’ trailblazing of Yumura Teruhiko, by Paul Gravett / ArtReview|last=name|first=Site|website=artreview.com|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref> ''Heta-uma'' can be translated as "bad but good", designating a work which looks poorly drawn, but with an aesthetically conscious quality, opposed to the polished look of mainstream manga.

Some of ''heta-uma''<nowiki/>'s main artists are [[Teruhiko Yumura]] (pen name "King Terry"),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.br/books?id=Z0yDAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=dreamland+japan&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dreamland%20japan&f=false|title=Dreamland Japan: Writings on Modern Manga|last=Schodt|first=Frederik L.|date=2014-01-02|publisher=Stone Bridge Press, Inc.|isbn=9781611725537|language=en}}</ref> [[Yoshikazu Ebisu]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.br/books?id=GvEFDD4rdWMC&pg=PT1266&lpg=PT1266&dq=yoshikazu+ebisu+hetauma&source=bl&ots=K01agSvJJu&sig=r4tTlaigwWGNy4H-ntpVmO1BQ7g&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirg426nJnQAhUJIZAKHc44AWs4ChDoAQg3MAU#v=onepage&q=yoshikazu%20ebisu%20hetauma&f=false|title=Manga: The Complete Guide|last=Thompson|first=Jason|date=2012-07-03|publisher=Random House Publishing Group|isbn=9780345539441|language=en}}</ref> and [[Takashi Nemoto]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.japantoday.com/category/arts-culture/view/avant-manga|title=Avant manga|newspaper=Japan Today|access-date=2016-11-08}}</ref>

